[This is the same case posted on 8 Sep 2018, with more details of the patient's convalescence (see Eastern equine encephalitis - USA (23): (MI) 20180919.6037655). The patient is fortunate to have survived his eastern equine encephalitis virus (EEEV) infection, although his neurological sequelae are not unusual in those who do survive.

As noted before, this has been an active year for transmission of EEEV in the eastern USA. This is the 1st human EEE case reported in Michigan this year (2018). Interestingly, no equine cases have been reported in the state this year (2018), although there was one in the neighboring state of Wisconsin.

Human EEE cases are very rare. Only a few cases are reported by CDC each year, occurring in the Atlantic and Gulf Coast states and very rarely in the Upper Midwest. Most cases of EEEV infection in humans are inapparent or mild with only 4.5 percent of cases severe. Severe cases occur most frequently in people under 15 and over 50 years of age. There is a 33 percent case fatality rate in severe cases, and survivors often have brain damage. There is no commercially available human vaccine, so avoidance of mosquito bites is the only preventive measure. Further information is available from CDC at https://www.cdc.gov/EasternEquineEncephalitis/. - Mod.TY

